  "text": "In order to identify genes with expression profiles that differ substantially among undifferentiated P6 spermatogonia (and might define subpopulations), we examined the expression levels (Log2ex values) of individual genes among the individual cells (Fig. 3) . This analysis was focused on cells isolated from Id4-eGFP mice because these cell preparations contained the fewest contaminating somatic cells (Figs. 1 and  2 ). As expected, the abundance of Id4 mRNA was largely uniform among Id4-eGFP þ cells (Fig. 3Ai , first three violin histograms-red, green, blue) and was detectable in nearly all GFP þ cells. GFP immunofluorescence staining in P6 Id4-eGFP testes (Fig. 3A , ii and iv, red) showed 100% colocalization with eGFP epifluorescence (Fig. 3A , iii and iv, green), which served as a baseline for all further colocalization studies. The majority of genes examined (122 of 172; Supplemental Fig. S9 and Supplemental Table S6 ) exhibited uniform mRNA abundance among Id4-eGFP þ spermatogonia, as demonstrated by limited normal distribution around a mean expression value (Fig. 3B , row i, red, green, and blue violin histograms in each plot). However, because of the greater heterogeneity in cell types isolated using THY1 þ MACS and StaPut, these mRNA levels were typically more heterogeneous in populations isolated by these methods (Fig. 3B , second group of violins [tan, purple, pink] and third group of violins [dark green, violet, maroon], respectively). Five exemplary gene products in this ''uniform mRNA abundance'' category (Fig. 3B , ai-Dazl, bi-Ddx4, ciFoxo1, di-Sohlh2, and ei-Zbtb16), among Id4-eGFP þ cells, were examined on the protein level by immunostaining P6 Id4-eGFP þ testes (Fig. 3B ). Among these, DAZL (Fig. 3Ba , ii-iv), DDX4 (Fig. 3Bb, ii-iv), FOXO1 (Fig. 3Bc , ii-iv), and ZBTB16 (Fig. 3Be , ii-iv) were found to be present uniformly among GFP þ cells. Although all DDX4 þ spermatogonia were GFP þ (Fig. 3Ba, i) , we found that 24% of DDX4 þ spermatogonia exhibited bright GFP þ epifluorescence and the remainder (76%) were GFP-dim (Fig. 3Ba, ii-iv, arrowheads) , consistent with previous observations [CITATION_1] . SOHLH2 protein, however, did not appear to be present at uniform levels among GFP þ cells (Fig. 3Bd, ii-iv) . Specifically, cells with dim GFP epifluorescence exhibited high apparent levels of SOHLH2 staining (Fig. 3Bd , ii-iv, arrows), whereas cells with high GFP epifluorescence had lower SOHLH2 staining (Fig. 3Bd , ii-iv, arrowheads), which is consistent with the proposed role of SOHLH2 in spermatogonial differentiation [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Similar results were observed for SOHLH1 (data not shown). Thus, although uniform mRNA levels typically predicted uniformity at the protein level, there was a disparity between mRNA and protein levels for certain genes, such as Sohlh1 and Sohlh2, which encode known markers of spermatogonial differentiation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
